<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-area-of-kites" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Area of Kites</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.5 Area of Polygons
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Specific Learning Outcome</title>
                <p>
                    Determine the area of quadrilaterals in different situations. Explore the area of polygons as used in real-life situations.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <li component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Grade Level</title>
            <p>10</p>
        </li>
        <li component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Estimated Duration</title>
            <p>40 minutes</p>
        </li>
        <p component="lesson-plan">
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Know</title>
                    <p>
                        The formula for the area of a kite: <m>\text{Area} = \frac{1}{2} \times d_1 \times d_2</m>, where <m>d_1</m> and <m>d_2</m> are the diagonals. Properties of kites include two pairs of adjacent sides equal and perpendicular diagonals. Trigonometric ratios can be used to find missing angles and side lengths.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Do</title>
                    <p>
                        Calculate the area of kites using the diagonal formula. Use trigonometry to find interior angles. Find the perimeter using Pythagoras' theorem.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Apply</title>
                    <p>
                        Solve real-life problems involving kite-shaped structures such as solar panels, landing zones, and playground designs.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-polygons/area-of-kites.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-polygons/step-by-step-guide_area-of-kites.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery (15 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            Students work in groups to complete the anchor activity: <em>Constructing a Kite Using Geometry Tools</em>. They will discover the properties of a kite by measuring sides, angles, and diagonals.
        </p>
        <p>
            <em>Teacher Role During Discovery:</em>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Circulate among groups, ensuring students understand how to use the compass and protractor correctly.</p></li>
                <li><p>Ask probing questions: <q>What do you notice about the adjacent sides?</q> <q>Are the diagonals perpendicular?</q></p></li>
                <li><p>For struggling groups: <q>Let us draw the first diagonal together. Make sure it is 10 cm long.</q></p></li>
                <li><p>For early finishers: <q>Can you calculate the area of your kite using the diagonals?</q></p></li>
                <li><p>Guide students to articulate: Two pairs of adjacent sides are equal, and the diagonals are perpendicular.</p></li>
                <li><p>Identify 2–3 groups with accurate constructions to share with the class.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_oebuaz02">
    <title>Constructing a Kite Using Geometry Tools</title> 
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_atiyzi35">
              How to construct a kite accurately using a ruler, compass, and protractor.   
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_emdzdnd5">
            <ul xml:id="auto_pus4gb6f">
                <li xml:id="auto_3vjazkik">
                    <p xml:id="auto_3r3be87e">
                     Materials needed:   
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_fq7pmhlr">
                    <p xml:id="auto_gclo4kqj">
                        Graph paper or plain paper
                    </p>
                    
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_pitujxw1">
                   <p xml:id="auto_j9l164c4">
                        Ruler , Compass, protractor, pencil and eraser
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_jz7esvsm">
                    <p xml:id="auto_l8rwl4dy">
                        Follow this steps.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_8ss31syq">
                      <m>  \textbf{Step 1:  Drawing the diagnol.}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ajrt2to4">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ujnd4tac">
                        Draw a vertical line of length 10 cm (this will be the longer diagonal, <m>d_1</m>).
                    </p>

                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_3avzuhlg">
                    <p xml:id="auto_6qlqa05l">
                        Label the midpoint of this line as O.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_bwt9xlnd">
                     <m>   \textbf{Step 2: Draw the Perpendicular Diagonal}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_0vx2cd9o">
                    <p xml:id="auto_jx893q0a">
                        At O, use a protractor to draw a perpendicular line.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_nms3tqyd">
                    <p xml:id="auto_9ia4kfwi">
                        Mark <m>4 \, \text{cm} </m> on each side of <m>O</m> (total shorter diagonal <m>d_2 = </m><m>8cm</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_0wefzsou">
                         <m>   \textbf{Step 3: Mark the Kite's Vertices}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_9b08q4pe">
                    <p xml:id="auto_rkwaqxn6">
                        Label the four points where the diagonals intersect as A, B, C, and D.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_nb5hrivj">
                    <p xml:id="auto_5t8gv8s6">
                        Connect <m>\textbf{A}</m> to <m>\textbf{B}</m>, <m>\textbf{B}</m> to <m>\textbf{C}</m>, <m>\textbf{C}</m> to <m>\textbf{D}</m> and <m>\textbf{D}</m> to <m>\textbf{A}</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_92rlm39p">
                        <m>   \textbf{Step 3:Check Properties }</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_tdif7tr9">
                    <p xml:id="auto_vi6gthry">
                        Measure adjacent sides to ensure two pairs are equal.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_4g8zoj2c">
                    <p xml:id="auto_579fwkcm">
                        Verify opposite angles (one pair should be equal)
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_6meew8y0">
                    <p xml:id="auto_9zyuls7t">
                        Confirm diagonals are perpendicular.

                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_xvxf6i9r">
                Design your own kite patterns on graph paper and justify why their design would be aerodynamic and stable in the air. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <insight>
        <p>
            A kite is a quadrilateral with two pairs of adjacent sides equal in length and one pair of opposite angles equal.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_bc12c7qy">
            A kite can be analyzed using coordinate geometry when its vertices are given on a Cartesian plane.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_94mrvnji">
            Since the diagonals are perpendicular, right-angled triangles are formed.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_capiv7md">
            We can use trigonometric ratios (sine, cosine, tangent) to find missing angles and side lengths.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_kss46zpv">
            <m>\textbf {Finding Angles Using Trigonometry} </m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_j2jv2owf">
            If a kite has diagonals <m>d_2</m> and <m> d_2</m> we can find interior angles using:
            <md>
                <mrow>\text{sin}\, \theta = \amp \frac{\text{ opposite side}} {\text{hypotenuse}}</mrow>
                <mrow>\text{cos}\, \theta = \amp \frac{\text{ adjacent side}} {\text{hypotenuse}}</mrow>
                <mrow>\text{tan}\, \theta = \amp \frac{\text{ opposite side}} {\text{adjacent side}}</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>

        <image width="50%">
        <latex-image label="kite">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                % Define the kite's vertices
                \coordinate (A) at (0,2);
                \coordinate (B) at (-1,0.7);
                \coordinate (C) at (1,0.7);
                \coordinate (D) at (0,-1);
                
                % Fill the kite with pink color
                
                % Draw the kite
                \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (D) -- (C) -- cycle;
                \draw[thick, dashed] (A) -- (D);
                \draw[thick, dashed] (B) -- (C);
                
                % Label the vertices
                \node[above] at (A) {A};
                \node[left] at (B) {B};
                \node[right] at (C) {C};
                \node[below] at (D) {D};
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
        </image>
        <p xml:id="auto_9003163y">
            If a kite has diagonals 14 cm and 10 cm, then each right-angled triangle within the kite has:
            <md>
                <mrow>\text{Base}=  \frac{d_1} {2}=\amp \frac{14}{2} </mrow>
                <mrow> \amp </mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp 7 \, \text{cm} </mrow>

                <mrow>\text{Height} = \frac{d_2}{2} =\amp \frac{10}{2} </mrow>
                <mrow> \amp </mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp 5 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
            </md>
            The angle θθ between the diagonal and a side can be found using:
            <md>
                <mrow> \text{tan} \, \theta = \amp \frac{5}{7} </mrow>
                <mrow>\theta = \amp  \text{tan}^{-1} \, 0.7143</mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp 35.5^ \circ </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction (10 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            After students have shared their findings from the anchor activity, formalize the area formula for kites. Direct students to the key takeaway and properties in their textbooks.
        </p>
        <p>
            <em>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions:</em>
        </p>
        <p>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                    <cell>Misconception</cell>
                    <cell>Clarification</cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell>All sides of a kite are equal.</cell>
                    <cell>Only two pairs of <em>adjacent</em> sides are equal.</cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell>The diagonals of a kite are equal.</cell>
                    <cell>The diagonals are usually not equal, but they are perpendicular.</cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell>I can use the formula for a rhombus.</cell>
                    <cell>Yes — the formula is the same because both have perpendicular diagonals.</cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell>A kite is the same as a square.</cell>
                    <cell>A square has all sides equal and all angles equal; a kite has only two pairs of adjacent sides equal.</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application (10 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            Direct students to the worked examples in the textbook. Students should work through each example with teacher guidance before attempting the exercises independently.
        </p>
        <p>
            <em>Teacher prompts:</em>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li><p><q>What formula do we use for the area of a kite?</q></p></li>
                <li><p><q>How do the diagonals help us find the right-angled triangles inside the kite?</q></p></li>
                <li><p><q>How can we use Pythagoras' theorem to find the side lengths?</q></p></li>
                <li><p><q>Which trigonometric ratio should we use to find the angle?</q></p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_sek53wxc">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_aktbtcng">
               A kite whose has the diagonals are 16 cm and 12 cm.</p>
            <p xml:id="auto_b81ed7o4">
                  a) Find the area of the a kite 
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_8lmdn9hq">
                b) If one pair of adjacent sides is 10 cm, find the perimeter of the kite.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_b79c2u4w">
                c) Find the angles of the kite using trigonometry.
            </p>
    <image width="50%">
    <latex-image label="kite-example">
        \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Define the kite's vertices
            \coordinate (A) at (0,2);
            \coordinate (B) at (-2,0.7);
            \coordinate (C) at (2,0.7);
            \coordinate (D) at (0,-1.5);
            
            % Fill the kite with pink color
            
            % Draw the kite
            \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (D) -- (C) -- cycle;
            \draw[thick, dashed] (A) -- (D);
            \draw[thick, dashed] (B) -- (C);
            
            % Label the vertices
            \node[above] at (A) {A};
            \node[left] at (B) {B};
            \node[right] at (C) {C};
            \node[below] at (D) {D};
            \node at (1,0.5) {16 cm};
            \node[above,rotate=90] at (0,0.5){12 cm};
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
    </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_vh7ollvg">
                <m>\textbf{ Find the Area of the Kite}</m>
                Let <m>d_1 = 16 \, \text{cm}</m> and <m>d_2 = 12 \, \text{cm}</m>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\textbf{Area} = \amp \frac{1}{2} \times d_1 \times d_2</mrow>
                </md>  
                <m>\text{substitute} \, d_1 = 16 \, \text{cm and } d_2 = 12 \, \text{cm}</m>
                <md>  
                    <mrow>\text{Area} = \amp \frac{1}{2} \times 16 \, \text{cm } \times 12 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{192}{2} \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 96 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_246yzffp">
             (b)  Find the Perimeter of the Kite.
             The diagonals bisect each other at right angles, so each half-diagonal forms a right-angled triangle.
             <m> \frac{d_1}{2} = 6\text { cm }</m> and <m>\frac{d_2}{2} = 8 \text{cm}</m>
             Using the Pythagoras Theorem:
             <md>
                <mrow> \amp a^2 + b^2 =  c^2</mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp 6^2 + 8^2</mrow>
                <mrow> c^2 = \amp 36 + 64</mrow>
                <mrow> \sqrt{c^2} = \amp \sqrt{100} </mrow>
                <mrow> c = \amp 10 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
             </md>
             Since a kite has two pairs of equal sides, the perimeter is:
             <md>
                <mrow> P  = \amp 2(a+b) </mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp 2(10 + 10) \, \text{cm}</mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp 40 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
             </md>

            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_4jvskctw">
               (c)  Finding the Angles Using Trigonometry. 
               Using trigonometry in the right-angled triangle:
               <md>
                <mrow> \text{tan} \, \theta = \amp \frac{\text{Opposite}}{\text{adjacent}} </mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp \frac{6}{8} </mrow>
                <mrow> \theta = \amp \text{tan}^{-1} \, 0.75 </mrow>
                <mrow> \amp </mrow>
                <mrow>\theta = \amp 36.87^\circ </mrow>
               </md>
               </p>
             <p xml:id="auto_ecni6htx">  A kite is a quadrilateral, meaning it has four angles.</p>
               <p xml:id="auto_wesrach9">The sum of the interior angles of any quadrilateral is given by the formula:</p>
                <p xml:id="auto_neuvcmzi">Sum of Interior Angles=<m>(n-2) \times 180^\circ</m></p>
                <p xml:id="auto_hfu4xsv6">where <m>n = 4</m><em>(since a kite has 4 sides)</em>
                <m>(4-2) \times 180^\circ </m>
                <m>= 2 \times 180^\circ</m>
                <m> = 360^\circ</m>
             </p>
             <p xml:id="auto_y0l5lr9q">
               Since the kite is symmetric, the larger angle ( <m> \alpha </m> )is
               <md>
                <mrow> = \amp 360^\circ - 2 \theta </mrow>
                <mrow>  = \amp 360^\circ - 2 (36.87)^\circ </mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp 360^\circ - 73.74 ^\circ  </mrow>
                <mrow> 2(\alpha)= \amp 286.26 ^\circ</mrow>
                <mrow> \alpha = \amp 143.13^\circ </mrow>
               </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_nr29o3av">
                The angles of the kite are:<m> 143^\circ, \, 143.13^\circ, \, 36.87^\circ \, \text{and} \, 36.87^\circ</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A kite has diagonals of lengths <m>18</m> cm and <m>14</m> cm.
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="kite-challenging">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \coordinate (A) at (0,3);
                        \coordinate (B) at (-3,0.8);
                        \coordinate (C) at (3,0.8);
                        \coordinate (D) at (0,-2);
                        \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (D) -- (C) -- cycle;
                        \draw[thick, dashed] (A) -- (D);
                        \draw[thick, dashed] (B) -- (C);
                        \node[above] at (A) {A};
                        \node[left] at (B) {B};
                        \node[right] at (C) {C};
                        \node[below] at (D) {D};
                        \node at (1.5,1.2) {18 cm};
                        \node[above,rotate=90] at (0,0.5){14 cm};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the area of the kite.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Determine all interior angles of the kite using trigonometry.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Area of the kite: 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>d_1 = 18 \; \text{cm}</m> and <m>d_2 = 14\; \text{cm}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Area} =  \amp \frac{1}{2} \times d_1 \times d_2</mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp \frac{1}{2} \times 18 \times 14</mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp 126 \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
                            </md>   
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Interior angles using trigonometry: 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Consider the triangle formed by half-diagonals:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\tan \theta = \frac{d_1/2}{d_2/2} = \frac{9}{7}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\theta = \tan^{-1}(\frac{9}{7})</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\theta \approx 52.13^\circ</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                           The other angles of the kite: 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\alpha = 180^\circ - 2 \theta = 180 - 2(52.13) \approx 75.74^\circ</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Therefore, the angles of the kite are approximately:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                           <m>75.74^\circ, 75.74^\circ, 104.26^\circ, 104.26^\circ</m> 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment (5 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            Students complete the following exit ticket questions individually.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li><p>Find the area of a kite with diagonals 10 cm and 8 cm.</p></li>
                <li><p>A playground has a kite-shaped design with diagonals measuring 15 metres and 12 metres. Find its area.</p></li>
                <li><p>A rescue helicopter designates an emergency landing zone in the shape of a kite. The diagonals measure 60 m and 45 m. Calculate the available landing space.</p></li>
                <li><p>Engineers are designing a kite-shaped solar panel with diagonals of 30 m and 18 m. What is the total solar-collecting area?</p></li>
                <li><p>A relief team sets up a kite-shaped safe zone for disaster survivors. The diagonals measure 50 m and 40 m. What is the area available for the survivors?</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            <em>Answer Key:</em>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li><p><m>\text{Area} = \frac{1}{2} \times 10 \times 8 = 40 \text{ cm}^2</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>\text{Area} = \frac{1}{2} \times 15 \times 12 = 90 \text{ m}^2</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>\text{Area} = \frac{1}{2} \times 60 \times 45 = 1{,}350 \text{ m}^2</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>\text{Area} = \frac{1}{2} \times 30 \times 18 = 270 \text{ m}^2</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>\text{Area} = \frac{1}{2} \times 50 \times 40 = 1{,}000 \text{ m}^2</m></p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the area of the kite given below.
                </p>
                <image width="60%">
                <latex-image label="kite-exercise">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (2,3) -- (4,0) -- (2,-3) -- cycle;
                        \draw[dashed] (2,3) -- (2,-3);
                        \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (4,0);
                        \node[below] at (1.5,-0.5) {6 cm};
                        \node[right] at (2.5,0.5) {4 cm};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                   <m>12\;\text{cm}^2</m> 
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A kite has diagonals of length <m>10</m> cm and <m>8</m> cm. Find its area.
                </p>
                <image width="60%">
                <latex-image label="kite-exercise-two">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (3,4) -- (6,0) -- (3,-4) -- cycle;
                        \draw[dashed] (3,4) -- (3,-4);
                        \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (6,0);
                        \node[below] at (3,-1) {10 cm};
                        \node[below] at (4,0) {8 cm};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                   <m>40\;\text{cm}^2</m> 
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A playground has a kite-shaped design with diagonals measuring <m>15</m> meters and <m>12</m> meters. Find its area.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>90 \;\text{m}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A rescue helicopter designates an emergency landing zone in the shape of a kite. The diagonals measure <m>60</m> m and <m>45</m> m. Calculate the available landing space.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>1350\;\text{m}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Engineers are designing a kite-shaped solar panel with diagonals of <m>30</m> m and <m>18</m> m. What is the total solar-collecting area?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>270\;\text{m}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A relief team sets up a kite-shaped safe zone for disaster survivors. The diagonals measure <m>50</m> m and <m>40</m> m. What is the area available for the survivors?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>1000 \;\text{m}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <p>
            <em>For Struggling Learners:</em>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Provide pre-drawn kites with diagonals already labelled.</p></li>
                <li><p>Use simpler numbers for diagonal lengths.</p></li>
                <li><p>Pair struggling students with confident problem solvers.</p></li>
                <li><p>Provide step-by-step calculation templates.</p></li>
                <li><p>Allow use of calculators.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <em>For On-Level Learners:</em>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Encourage students to draw their own kites from word problems.</p></li>
                <li><p>Ask students to explain which formula they chose and why.</p></li>
                <li><p>Provide mixed practice with both finding area and finding missing dimensions.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <em>For Advanced Learners:</em>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Challenge students to derive the formula themselves using the concept of perpendicular diagonals.</p></li>
                <li><p>Explore real-world applications: kite design, architecture, solar panel design.</p></li>
                <li><p>Investigate the relationship between the area of a kite and other quadrilaterals.</p></li>
                <li><p>Apply trigonometry to find all angles when given only the diagonals.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Extension Activity</title>
        <p>
            <em>Real-World Application: Designing Kite-Shaped Structures</em>
        </p>
        <p>
            Students work in groups to design a kite-shaped structure (solar panel, landing zone, playground, safe zone) and calculate its area.
        </p>
        <p>
            Materials: Graph paper, rulers, protractors, calculators, coloured pencils.
        </p>
        <p>
            Tasks:
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li><p>Choose a real-world application that uses kite shapes.</p></li>
                <li><p>Draw the kite on graph paper with appropriate dimensions.</p></li>
                <li><p>Measure or specify the lengths of both diagonals.</p></li>
                <li><p>Calculate the area using the formula <m>\text{Area} = \frac{1}{2} \times d_1 \times d_2</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>If applicable, use trigonometry to find the angles of the kite.</p></li>
                <li><p>Present your findings to the class, explaining your design choices and calculations.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

